<div class="eva-slice eva-slice-1">
	<h3 class="eva-title">Indian Navy</h3>
	<div class="eva-content">
		<p>
			Started as Royal Indian Navy, the Indian Navy has come a long way since independence to emerge as one of the strongest naval forces in the world. With over 58,000 personnel and a huge operational fleet, it plays a very important role in the country’s defence.<br/>
 The naval exhibition will showcase the different aspects of the navy and put on display the various models of the noteworthy ships as nuclear submarine INS Chakra and aircraft carrier INS Vikramaditya. The naval exhibition will include a complete overview of the Indian Naval Academy which is the single largest naval training establishment, the detailed explanation of the procedures and workings of electronics warfare and information technology systems and a stunning display of arms and navigation systems. In a nutshell, the exhibitions will reveal the intricacies of one of our finest organisations.

		</p>

	</div>
</div>
<div class="eva-slice eva-slice-2">
	<h3 class="eva-title">ISRO</h3>
	<div class="eva-content">
		<p>
			“Space exploration is a force of nature unto itself that no other force in society can rival.” -Neil deGrasse Tyson.<br/>
 ISRO, The Indian Space Research Organization is an institution with unmatched reputation in the country for its successful missions and contributions to the nation. It is instrumental in catapulting India into the elite club of global space research. The secrets of space have been unraveled and made within reach by ISRO.<br/>
The exhibition will showcase models of various projects of ISRO which include The Polar Satellite Launch Vehicle PSLV, The Geosynchronous Satellite Launch Vehicle (GSLV), the Chandrayaan-1, India’s first lunar mission. Models of different satellites, their components, the working principles will also be exhibited.
		</p>
	</div>
</div>
<div class="eva-slice eva-slice-3">
	<h3 class="eva-title"> RIG </h3>
	<div class="eva-content">
		<p>
			The Robotics Interest Group (RIG) at NIT Calicut is an interdisciplinary group of students united by a passion towards robotics and automation. The group focuses on undertaking research and development projects in the field of robotic technology, participating in prominent contests involving robotics and imparting its knowledge and expertise to juniors and society in general.<br/>
